zed form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda was born about 1330, in Staveley, Lancashire, England. She married Robert Staveley about 1350, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1370–1410":"1370–1410","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1337":"1337","ABT 1350":"umbes 1350","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1370":"1370","1319":"1319",",,, England":"Inglismaa, Un